{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17610469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17610469"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:01:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:01:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16174"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16174"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.21,0.07,0.57,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8865"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74597"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8865"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60091"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5322"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"10592"},{"type":"tags","id":"10640"},{"type":"tags","id":"10648"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21115"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74597"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of alveolar epithelial cells in the lactating breast?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regulation of breast tissue blood flow","Transport of minerals into breast milk","Storage of maternal antibodies","Production and secretion of milk proteins and lipids","Production of growth factors for infant development"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of mammary alveolar epithelial cells is milk production and secretion during lactation. These cells undergo significant changes during pregnancy and lactation in response to hormonal signals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction and secretion of milk proteins and lipids\u003C/strong\u003E is the main function of alveolar epithelial cells. These cells synthesise milk proteins such as casein and whey proteins, and produce lipid droplets that are secreted into milk. This process is primarily controlled by prolactin, while milk ejection is triggered by oxytocin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStorage of maternal antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary function of alveolar cells. Immunoglobulins (particularly IgA) are transferred into breast milk through specialised transport mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport of minerals\u003C/strong\u003E into breast milk occurs but is a secondary function. Calcium, phosphate, and other minerals are actively transported across alveolar cells, but this is not their primary role.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of growth factors\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in breast tissue, but this is not the main function of alveolar cells. While breast milk contains growth factors, these are produced by various cell types in the mammary gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulation of breast tissue blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E is not a function of alveolar cells. This is controlled by the surrounding vasculature and regulatory mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alveolar epithelial cells in the breast produce and secrete milk proteins and lipids during lactation.","Prolactin stimulates milk protein synthesis while oxytocin triggers milk ejection from alveolar cells.","Alveolar cells undergo significant proliferation and differentiation during pregnancy in preparation for lactation."],"references":["Zucca-Matthes G, Urban C, Vallejo A. Anatomy of the nipple and breast ducts. Gland Surg. 2016 Feb;5(1):32-6. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2227-684X.2015.05.10. PMID: 26855906; PMCID: PMC4716863.","Javed A, Lteif A. Development of the human breast. Semin Plast Surg. 2013 Feb;27(1):5-12. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1343989. PMID: 24872732; PMCID: PMC3706056.","Biswas SK, Banerjee S, Baker GW, Kuo CY, Chowdhury I. The Mammary Gland: Basic Structure and Molecular Signaling during Development. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Mar 31;23(7):3883. doi: 10.3390/ijms23073883. PMID: 35409243; PMCID: PMC8998991.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60091"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16174"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60091"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T18:57:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T07:54:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8865"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74597"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag